## Theoretical Expectation

Pure arithmetic complexity predicts:

```text
Doubling N → Execution Time × 8
```

because:

```text
Matrix multiplication performs O(N³) operations.
```

If computation alone determined performance, all growth factors would remain close to 8.

---

## Observations

The experimental results deviated significantly from ideal cubic scaling.

### Small Matrices (32–256)

Execution time increased relatively smoothly.

The processor was able to retain a large fraction of the working data inside the cache hierarchy.

Performance was primarily determined by arithmetic throughput.

```text
Compute-bound regime.
```

---

### Medium Matrices (512–1024)

Execution times began increasing more rapidly.

Estimated working sets:

```text
512 × 512  → approximately 3 MB
1024 × 1024 → approximately 12 MB
```

At these sizes:

* L1 cache was exceeded.
* L2 cache effectiveness decreased.
* L3 cache became increasingly important.

Both arithmetic operations and memory traffic contributed significantly to execution time.

```text
Mixed compute-memory regime.
```

---

### Large Matrices (2056–4096)

Estimated working sets:

```text
2056 × 2056 → approximately 50 MB
4096 × 4096 → approximately 201 MB
```

Execution times grew dramatically:

```text
1024 → 2056 : 1.87 s → 18.29 s
2056 → 4096 : 18.29 s → 356.17 s
```

The observed growth factor reached:

```text
19.47×
```

instead of the theoretically expected:

```text
8×
```

At this point, the processor spent much of its time waiting for data to arrive from main memory.

```text
Memory-bound regime.
```

---

## Interpretation

The experiment revealed three distinct performance regions:

### Region 1: Compute-Bound

```text
Small matrices
↓
Most data fits in cache
↓
Arithmetic dominates
```

---

### Region 2: Transition Region

```text
Medium matrices
↓
Caches begin overflowing
↓
Memory traffic increases
↓
Both computation and data movement matter
```

---

### Region 3: Memory-Bound

```text
Large matrices
↓
Working set exceeds cache hierarchy
↓
DRAM accesses dominate
↓
Processor stalls waiting for data
```

---

## Key Insight

This experiment demonstrates that algorithmic complexity alone is insufficient to predict real-world performance.

Although matrix multiplication requires:

```text
O(N³)
```

operations, the cost of moving data through the memory hierarchy eventually dominates the cost of performing arithmetic.

The processor transitions from:

```text
"Compute-limited"

to

"Memory-limited."
```

as the problem size increases.

---

## Conclusion

This experiment provided direct empirical evidence of the **memory wall**.

Without using hardware profilers or cache specifications, simply varying matrix size revealed how processor performance changes across different levels of the memory hierarchy.

The results support one of the central principles of High Performance Computing:

> Moving data efficiently is often more important than performing arithmetic efficiently.

Two implementations with identical mathematical complexity can exhibit vastly different performance depending on how effectively they utilize the cache hierarchy.

As problem sizes grow, memory behavior becomes the dominant factor governing execution time.
